
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `atobm` (ASCII to Binary Map) yek barname baraye tabdil kardane file-haye ASCII pixmap (XPM) be formate binary XBM ast. In barname bishtar baraye sakhte tasvirhaye koochak baraye barname-haye GUI estefade mishavad. 🖼️

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `atobm -name <esme_tasvir>` --> 🏷️ Esme tasvir dar file XBM ra moshakhas mikonad. Agar esme tasvir ra moshakhas nakonid, esme file XPM be onvane esme tasvir estefade mishavad.
    🔹 `atobm -install` --> 💾 File XBM ra dar directory `/usr/include/X11/bitmaps` zakhire mikonad. (be dastresi admin niaz darad)
    🔹 `atobm -version` --> ℹ️ Nemayeshe versione barname.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ atobm logo.xpm > logo.xbm

    🔹 Tabdil kardane file `logo.xpm` be `logo.xbm`.

    $ atobm -name my_icon icon.xpm > my_icon.xbm

    🔹 Tabdil kardane `icon.xpm` be `my_icon.xbm` va esme tasvir ra `my_icon` gharar midehad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ atobm -name check_mark check.xpm > check_mark.xbm

    🔹 File `check.xpm` ra be formate `check_mark.xbm` tabdil mikonad, va esme tasvir dar file XBM `check_mark` mishavad. In yek tasvir koochak baraye yek dokme ya checkbox misazad. ✔️

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `atobm` (ASCII to Binary Map) command converts ASCII pixmap (XPM) files to binary XBM format. This is commonly used for creating small images for GUI applications. 🖼️

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `atobm -name <image_name>` --> 🏷️ Specifies the name of the image in the XBM file. If you don't specify the image name, the XPM filename is used as the image name.
    🔹 `atobm -install` --> 💾 Saves the XBM file to the `/usr/include/X11/bitmaps` directory. (Requires administrative privileges)
    🔹 `atobm -version` --> ℹ️ Displays the program version.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ atobm logo.xpm > logo.xbm

    🔹 Converts the `logo.xpm` file to `logo.xbm`.

    $ atobm -name my_icon icon.xpm > my_icon.xbm

    🔹 Converts `icon.xpm` to `my_icon.xbm` and sets the image name to `my_icon`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ atobm -name check_mark check.xpm > check_mark.xbm

    🔹 Converts the `check.xpm` file to `check_mark.xbm`, and the image's name inside the XBM file will be `check_mark`. This creates a small image suitable for a button or checkbox. ✔️
